passages.text: Rising Tides - FY25 result

ASB delivered \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 113\mathrm{m}\) of EBIT in FY25, significantly ahead of consensus expectations \((+19\%)\) . After backing out the A\\$6.3m uplift from the accounting treatment of the MMF3 facility, the \(+13\%\) earnings beat was driven by a strong Australasian print, more than offsetting earnings declines in US Shipbuilding. Beyond the growing order book, we expect near- term earnings to remain supported by the recognition of MMF3 proceeds. While tailwinds are clearly evident, we retain our Neutral rating on valuation grounds but also note elevated operational risk as ASB undertakes multiple new shipbuilding programs. PT A\\$7.10.

MMF3 contract boosts earnings. ASB confirmed accounting treatment of the US\\$450m submarine manufacturing contract; US\\$350m ( \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 526\mathrm{m}\) ) was invoiced and paid in FY25. Of the US\\$350m, ASB has estimated a revenue/ earnings uplift of \(\mathrm{A}\S 6.2\mathrm{m}\) in FY25, \(\mathrm{A}\S 23.3\mathrm{m}\) in FY26 and \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 59\mathrm{m}\) per annum over the remaining 8.5 years as performance obligations are met. Worth noting, a release of \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 59\mathrm{m}\) suggests a \(40\%\) uplift to cons FY27 EBIT estimates (A \(\S 148\mathrm{m}\) ). ASB has paid tax of \(\sim \mathrm{U}\S \S 80\mathrm{m}\) on the US\\$350m invoiced with a direct drop down to the bottom line. This drives earnings upgrades of FY26/27 EBIT \(+10\% / + 14\%\) ; however, these provisions unwind and are non- cash. The remaining US\\$100m is expected to be booked towards the end of construction.

Return to profitability. ASB reported FY25 EBIT of A\\$113m, following the pre- guide of \(\geq \mathrm{A}\S 100\mathrm{m}\) . Backing out \(\sim \mathrm{S}6\mathrm{m}\) of MMF3 proceeds recognised in FY25, ASB's underlying EBIT would have been \(\S 107\mathrm{m}\) . The key driver of the result was the turnaround in Australasia Ship Building with a \(\S 46\mathrm{m}\) earnings swing (FY25 EBIT of \(\S 24\mathrm{m}\) vs FY24 EBIT of \(\cdot \S 22\mathrm{m}\) ) largely driven by improved utilisation in the Philippines/Vietnam yoy and continued LCM activity. US Shipbuilding EBIT reduced \(- 15\%\) vs pcp with margins falling \(\sim 100\mathrm{bps}\) vs pcp due to completion of higher- margin LCS and EPF contracts and a continued drag from onerous contracts (AFDM and T- ATS). The T- ATS REA is expected to be finalised in 1H26.

Cash flow and balance sheet. ASB delivered a strong cash performance, ending the year in a net cash position of \(\S 453\mathrm{m}\) and NOCF of \(\S 406\mathrm{m}\) with a significant uptick due to milestone receipts MMF3 and capital proceeds. Excluding the milestone payments, a \(\sim \S 200\mathrm{m}\) inventory build (due to complications with the T- ATS program) was a drag on working capital but partly offset by a shortening of the invoice cycle in Australasia.

Earnings & Valuation: At Jun- 25, the company had an order book (incl. options) of \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 13.1\mathrm{bn}\) , diversified across multiple programs. The SSA signing is expected to generate significant order book growth in 1H26 with the 'LCM' program alone expected to be A\\$1.0- 1.3bn. ASB highlighted the possibility of 'LCM' and 'LCH' programs to contribute \(\sim \mathrm{A}\S 5\mathrm{bn}\) to the order book by CY25 end. Our FY26/27 earnings increase (EBIT \(+10\% / + 14\%\) ) along with our comp- co multiples. Acknowledging the significant industry tailwinds we remain Neutral given our upgraded PT (A\\$7.10) remains below the share price.

Austal (ASB) designs and manufactures customised aluminium defence and commercial vessels; its customers include many of the world's leading ferry operators and defence forces.

The company's primary earnings driver is its US shipyard, which is in the process of transitioning from a mature aluminium- based shipbuilding programme (LCS) to steel shipbuilding programmes. The company has been awarded several different steel- based construction contracts. While we remain cautious on the outlook for shipbuilding margins, given the nature of new programmes using steel, the company has a very large order book and is widely diversified by vessel and customer.

Our June 2026 share price target of A\$7.10 is based on our blended DCF valuation (WACC: \(11.0\%\) , Forecast period: 10 years, Terminal value: assumes the company does not generate ROIC above WACC in perpetuity) and listed compco- based valuation. Our price target is based on the future value of our valuation, less any dividends to be paid between now and the target date.

The signing of the SSA is expected to generate significant order book growth in 1H26 with 'LCM' program alone expected to be A \(\) 1.0- 1.3bn (finalised in \(\sim\) 1Q26). ASB has highlighted the possibility of 'Landing Craft Medium' and 'LCH' programs to contribute \(\sim\) A \(\) 5bn\$ to the order book by end CY25. Combined with the accounting adjustments discussed (non- cash), our FY26/27 earnings (EBIT \(+10\% / + 14\%)\) have increased.
